WebQL is a JSON-based web scraping query language, not SQL. WebQL uses:
- JSON structure with @url, @steps, @xpath, @fields
- XPath selectors for HTML elements
- No SELECT/FROM statements

Example WebQL:
{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='item']",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

SQL is for databases, WebQL is for web scraping.

WebQL and GraphQL are completely different:

**WebQL** (Web scraping):
- JSON structure with @url, @steps, @xpath
- Uses XPath to extract HTML elements
- For scraping websites directly

**GraphQL** (API queries):
- query { field { subfield } } syntax
- Uses schema-defined resolvers
- For querying APIs with predefined schemas

WebQL example:
{
  "@url": "https://site.com",
  "@steps": [{
    "@xpath": "//a",
    "@fields": {"link": "./@href"}
  }]
}

GraphQL example:
query { users { name email } }

That's SQL syntax, not WebQL. The correct WebQL syntax is:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

WebQL uses JSON structure with @url, @steps, @xpath, and @fields - never SQL SELECT/FROM statements.

That's GraphQL syntax. WebQL uses JSON structure:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//span[@class='name']/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

WebQL uses @url, @steps, @xpath, @fields - not GraphQL's query {} syntax.

{
  "@url": "https://target-website.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//element-selector",
      "@name": "optional_step_name",
      "@fields": {
        "field1": ".//xpath-to-data/text()",
        "field2": ".//xpath-to-attribute/@href"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key components:
- @url: Target website
- @steps: Array of extraction steps
- @xpath: XPath selector for elements
- @fields: Data to extract from each element
